comment: Initial commit.
Update sample README to indicate we need hameno's fork for now.
Add image to readme.

Use new detection method which looks to see if the native ActionBar class is present. This should provide the most accurate answer as to whether or not the native ActionBar is supported. With this change comes the renaming of the classes from being Honeycomb* and PreHoneycomb* to Native* and GreenDroid*.
Complete rewrite!
Add javadoc documentation to classes.
Move references to GreenDroid and Android-ActionBar libraries to where I specify they should be in the READMEs.
Update README to reflect 2.0 changes.
Add change log.
Add README in samples about third-party library dependencies.
Update sample apps to include buttons with icons on both native and third-party action bars.
Add links to direct .apk downloads.
Date change log for 2.0.0.
Push back API levels. Not sure why I was only targeting 2.1+.
Use Class.forName() for detection of native ActionBar. This allows for compatability with every version of Android all the way back to 1.5.
While Android-ActionBar runs on Android 1.5 the layout is severely damaged. Android 1.6 is the minimum for proper rendering.
Detail version support more thoroughly in the README.
Bump version to 2.0.1.
Stupid Windows committed a case-insensitive library reference to GreenDroid.

Add activity base class which will automatically facilitate the inflation of XML menu files to either the native action bar or pass via a callback to the handler (assuming they implement an interface) for the manual adding of buttons.
Pass the whole menu for inflation to the handler.
Make the handler bubble the clicked event up to the activity. Use a custom Action for our action bar to do this.
Extract menu and menu item implementing classes to their own files.
Allow direct inflation to the action bar if it implements the Menu interface.
Simplify ActionBarMenu and ActionBarMenuItem creation.
Always enable the home icon which will return a proper id to mimic native ActionBar.
Use direct package reference to the native action bar.
Add homeAsUp(boolean) to API. This will call through to setDisplayHomeAsUpEnabled(boolean) for the native action bar and can optionally be implemented in custom handlers as well.
Support hinting the home button goes 'up' in Android-ActionBar handler.
Code cleanup and JavaDocs addition.
Call homeIsUp in the Android-ActionBar example and use a string resource rather than a hardcoded version.

Add sub-menu support. In the Android-ActionBar implementation we handle this via an AlertDialog that displays as a list. If your action bar supports dropdowns or popup lists this would allow for an even more elegant solution.
Update change log to reflect our progress so far.
Change log wording change.

* Implement a deprected ListActivity helper class. Fragments should be used when dealing with lists rather than using a ListActivity directly, but this might help for porting purposes as an intermediate step. * Move third-party menu XML inflation to the attach() method which greatly reduces the amount of code needed in the helper classes. * Require activity classes extend from our Activity or ListActivity helpers when adding a menu XML resource. * Throw an exception if neither the handler nor third-party action bar itself are capable of receiving an inflated menu XML.
Update interface names.
Add support for logos. Closes #3.
Simplfy activity logo reflection thanks to smith324. Add useLogo method to change log.
Organize imports.
Correctly name API method... idiot.

Add wrapper for a fragments activity which uses the compatibility library. At ~101KB, the effect should be minimal. The vast majority implementors will likely be using fragments so its added filesize would have been incured anyway.
Update sample to reflect new interface names.
Add fragment layout support to the API and native handler. Update Android-ActionBar and GreenDroid handlers in the samples to support.
Port the Shakespeare fragments demo from the ApiDemos to use the library.
Add drop-down support. Closes #4.
Add more assertions during the build process. Actually set attached to true when attach() is called.
Simplify logo usage and remove its logic from the attach() method.
Reorder activity base class list so the phrase 'the latter of which' actually refers to the right class.
Simplify menu usage and remove its logic rom the attach() method.
Move attachment logic when no appropriate handler is present to its own method.

Remove description of activity extending from our fragment activity base class when using fragments. All that is required is that it at least extend from the fragment activity class in the compatibility method itself.
Add messages to all assertions. Put all messages into private static final Strings.
Add missing comments. Remove unneeded ones.
Update samples a bit for new handler APIs.
Fix wording in class description.

For the time being, I am including Eclipse .project and .classpath files to ease in using the IDE to develop this library. Until the m2eclipse-android-plugin properly supports apklib dependencies as specified by maven, these project files will provide a much easier entry than attempting to set up the projects individually.
CRLF fixes.
Finalize implementations of interfaces in the native handler.
Spelling.
Only worry about native handler if we need it.

Add custom menu XML inflater which will essentially backport the new attributes to be available on pre-3.0 devices. Third-party handlers can now easily differentiate between items that must be displayed on the action bar and items which belong in an overflow menu (usually, the activity menu). Closes #10.

Resolve errors with referencing the native handler in methods that will be accessed from pre-3.0 initialization. The fallback to native handler functionality should still operate the same but no longer can we check that the custom handler does not extend from the native handler. A better solution will likely be to check the classname of the generic argument to the handler passed as the custom handler to make sure it does not match the native action bar's class name.
Use proper android namespace for fetching XML properties in the custom menu inflater.
Update @hameno GreenDroid version.
Load the title resource ID and pass that to the menu item.
Abstract some calls to the action bar through the handler.
Add internal tracking of HasXXX interfaces to native ActionBar methods. This will have to be moved somewhere more visible before release.
Remove helper methods for things such as title, menu, and home as up. These should now be accessed through the `HasXXX` interfaces only.
Update to build against Android 3.1 (API level 12).
Add honeycomb gallery sample into the mix. This is a straight import and it is currently not configured to work with the library.

Only use ObjectAnimator if we have the action bar. In reality we should use a seperate check since theoretically the presence of the native action bar does not correspond to the presence of the ObjectAnimator class.
Add HasCustomView interface.
HasListNavigation and HasTabNavigation each implement their own method to determine and set the selected item.
Change HasHomeAsUp to HasHome and implement the visibility toggle. Add partial implementation to GreenDroid handler.
Add show custom view toggle to HasCustomView interface.
Renamed some method names to be prefixed with 'set' rather than just the action-oriented name.
Add HasBackgroundDrawable interface for setting a custom background drawable on the action bar.
Make sure all native handler methods are final as they are just marshalls to the native methods.
Move the native action bar handler to the appropriate subpackage where the other handlers live.
Display options are not available, query getters on HasXXX interfaces for current display status.
Add height getter to HasVisibility interface.
Change menu listener methods to support adding and removing rather than just setting a single one.
Fix method map spacing.
Remove Eclipse .project and .classpath files. Update instructions for importing into a new Android project instead.

BOOM GOES THE DYNAMITE! Yet another almost complete rewrite, integration of the compatability library, and integration of Android-ActionBar for easy, out-of-the-box action bars, fragments, and loaders on every Android platform 1.6 and newer.
Merge the Android Compatibility Library r2 sources.
Add unified theme support. Not as elegant as I'd hoped but at least it'll only require the creation of a single theme.
Add all MDPI variations on the tab backgrounds taken from a Honeycomb system dump and re-9-patched.
Add HDPI variations on the tab background taken from a Honeycomb system dump and re-9-patched. Add pre-9-patched source PNGs.
Load application icon and show by default and fix the title loading.
Fix for list navigation dropdown not being able to be focused.
Make sure the logo and icon are clickable views.
Use a more appropriately named view for the list items.
Remove ActionMode support from this release :(. Simplify ActionBar implementation logic by automatically forwarding simple method calls to more complex implementations in the base class.
Menu inflation and adding the overflow menu as the context is now (mostly) working.
Rename Activity back to FragmentActivity since that is what most people will be using who already utilize the compat lib.

Simplify menu inflation technique. Allow for proper invalidation of pre- and post-3.0 menus. Remove access to onPrepareOptionsMenu since I currently cannot fathom where it would be called now that we are managing the invalidation and inflation of the menu manually.
Fix fragment animation on pre-3.0.
Execute the callback in activity when an action item is clicked and the listener (if any) didn't already handle it.
Add custom views to action items. Properly support action item callbacks.
Resolve error when a label is specified directly rather than with a string resource ID.
Tweaks to the HoneycombGallery sample to begin to get it working on pre-3.0. Still needs a lot of work.
Set exclusive checkable when adding a menu item to another menu. Closes #21.
Remove registering of a custom action bar handler for pre-3.0 devices. Other classes are far too specialized at the moment to allow for a custom handler to function properly.
Add dark indicators for the light theme. Not yet enabled.
Set initialized navigation mode to an invalid value so we ensure reloadDisplay() is called when setting default navigation mode in performAttach().
Re-enable some honeycomb specific functionality in the HoneycombGallery app.
Add ActionMode support for Android 3.0+ using our support classes. Refs #19.
Do not import the callback explicitly.

Rewrite of menu handling and inflation to use the native Menu instance via a wrapper when on post-3.0. This allows us to remain forwards compatibile with any new features introduced to the menu XML schema while still supporting whatever we want on older platforms via the custom inflater.

* Move action bar handler instantiation inside the activity constructor. * General code convention cleanup. * Do not use 'Honeycomb' in the name of the wrappers since they are sometimes used to wrap instances on all versions of the platform.
Add proper onPrepareOptionsMenu() support. Closes #20. This also introduces debugging statements that will be compiled out as long as the DEBUG variable is set to false.
Re-enable the onPrepareOptionsMenu callback in the honeycomb gallery sample after the last commit.
Add recreate() emulation for pre-honeycomb.
Use normal invalidate menu method signature since it is just an argument-less void method.
Add action item support to the feature demo.

* Abstract our custom action bar implementation to be a standalone widget. This affords us the ability to use it for both the action bar and an action mode at the same time. It also would allow someone to use the widget without fully utilizing the automatic action bar abstraction. * Rework themes to mimic those of the Android 3.0+ native themes except as Theme.Sherlock and Theme.Sherlock.Light. These automatically inherit from the appropriate parent themes based on platform.

Use the item view concept (used by Android internally) for our custom menu implementation which allows holding on to instance of the Menu and MenuItems, interacting with them asynchronously, and having those interactions reflected in either the action bar or options menu views.
Use proper styling for the list navigation dropdown.
Add special casing for the home item since it needs to have a corresponding MenuItem instance for the activity callback.
